<Primer
  title="At Inference Time"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models · Chapter Six"
  deck="A trained potential gives you a cheap energy and cheap forces. This chapter spends them."
  running="Ch. 6 — At Inference Time"
  prev={{ href: url('/primer/what-mlips-keep'), label: "What an MLIP Keeps — and Can't" }}
>
  <p class="lead">
    The potential takes an arrangement of atoms and returns one energy and the force on every atom —
    the same two quantities a DFT calculation hands back, but in milliseconds instead of hours. That
    speed is the whole point, and it changes what you can do with the energy landscape from Chapter 1.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 1</span>Relaxation: roll downhill until the forces vanish</h2>

  <p>
    Start with the simplest thing you can ask. You have a guessed arrangement of atoms — a candidate
    crystal, a molecule sketched by hand, a defect dropped into a lattice — and you want the stable
    version of it: the arrangement nature would actually settle into. On the landscape, "stable" means
    a valley floor. Nudge any atom and the energy goes up; that is what makes it a resting place.
  </p>

  <p>
    A valley floor is exactly where the slope is zero, so the force on every atom is zero. That gives
    you a procedure. Read the forces at your guessed arrangement. They point downhill, toward lower
    energy. Take a small step in that direction. Read the forces again at the new arrangement; step
    again. Each step lowers the energy, the forces shrink, and you coast to a stop at the bottom of the
    valley. This downhill walk is called <strong>relaxation</strong>, or geometry optimization, and the
    arrangement it lands on is the relaxed structure.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
