    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 1</span>Relaxation. From a guessed arrangement, step in the direction the forces point — downhill — until the forces shrink to nothing at a valley floor. That floor is the stable structure.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    With DFT this was painful: every step needs a fresh energy and forces, every reading takes hours,
    and a relaxation can run for dozens of steps. With a potential each reading is milliseconds, so the
    whole walk finishes in a moment. And once one structure is cheap, a thousand are cheap. You can
    relax thousands of candidate arrangements and keep the ones that settle lowest — the practical
    engine behind screening new materials.
  </p>

  <aside class="sidenote">
    <span class="sn-label">One caution</span>
    Rolling downhill finds <em>a</em> valley, the nearest one, not necessarily the deepest. A landscape
    has many valleys, and relaxation stops at whichever floor your starting guess drains into. Finding
    the lowest valley of all is a separate and harder search; relaxation only takes you to the bottom of
    the basin you started in.
  </aside>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 2</span>Molecular dynamics: step the atoms through time</h2>

  <p>
    Relaxation finds where atoms come to rest. But atoms at any real temperature do not rest — they
    move, jostle, and trade energy. To watch that, you let them move under their own forces, one tiny
    instant at a time.
  </p>

  <p>
    The loop is short. Take the current positions and read the force on every atom. A force is a push,
    and a push makes a mass accelerate — heavier atoms respond less, lighter ones more. So the forces
    tell you how every atom's velocity changes over a very short slice of time — a femtosecond, a
    millionth of a billionth of a second — call it one <strong>time-step</strong>;
    the velocities tell you how the positions change over that same slice. Apply both and you have a new
    arrangement, a sliver of time later. Read the forces there and repeat. Step and repeat, step and
    repeat — this is <strong>molecular dynamics</strong>, and the arrangement traced out step by step is
    a <strong>trajectory</strong>.
  </p>

  <figure class="fig">
    <div class="fig-frame">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 720 250" role="img" aria-label="A four-stage cycle: positions feed into the model, the model returns forces, forces update velocities and positions, and the loop repeats.">
