        <line x1="440" y1="46" x2="512" y2="100" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch6arrB)" />
        <line x1="560" y1="146" x2="442" y2="196" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch6arrB)" />
        <line x1="280" y1="208" x2="150" y2="146" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch6arrB)" />
        <line x1="150" y1="100" x2="280" y2="46" stroke="var(--ink)" stroke-width="1.2" marker-end="url(#ch6arrB)" />

        <text x="360" y="128" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it" style="font-size:13px;">milliseconds per step,</text>
        <text x="360" y="146" text-anchor="middle" class="svg-serif-it" style="font-size:13px;">millions of steps</text>

        <defs>
          <marker id="ch6arrB" markerWidth="9" markerHeight="9" refX="7" refY="4.5" orient="auto"><path d="M0 0 L9 4.5 L0 9 z" fill="var(--ink)"/></marker>
        </defs>
      </svg>
    </div>
    <figcaption><span class="fig-num">Fig. 2</span>The molecular-dynamics loop: from positions, the potential returns forces; the forces update the velocities and positions; one time-step later the loop runs again.</figcaption>
  </figure>

  <p>
    This is the cheap mirror of the slow loop Chapter 1 described. There, each step asked DFT for the
    energy and forces, so a trajectory of any length was hopeless — millions of femtosecond steps are
    needed to see anything happen. Replace the DFT reading with a potential reading and the cost per
    step collapses. Now those millions of steps are routine: where DFT dynamics reaches tens of
    picoseconds on tens of atoms, a potential runs nanoseconds on millions. The impossible regime from
    Chapter 1 becomes an afternoon.
  </p>

  <p>
    One piece is missing. Left alone, the loop holds total energy nearly constant — what it cannot do is
    fix the temperature. To run at, say, room
    temperature, you attach a <strong>thermostat</strong>: a small adjustment, applied each step, that
    gently nudges the atoms' speeds up or down to hold the average kinetic energy at the value
    corresponding to the target temperature. Set the thermostat to 300 kelvin and the simulation runs as
    if the sample sat in a 300-kelvin room.
  </p>

  <p>
    With that, you can watch processes, not just resting structures. Heat a crystal past its melting
    point and see the lattice give way to a liquid. Track a single atom wandering through a solid over
    time — <strong>diffusion</strong>. Pull on a slab until a <strong>crack</strong> starts — a line of
    broken bonds — and watch that line advance one bond at a time as the front reaches each atom. Press
    two materials together and watch the interface between them settle.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 3</span>Derived quantities: reading more off the surface</h2>

  <p>
    Chapter 5 named these as derivatives of the energy; here is how you read them off the landscape
    cheaply. Sit at a valley floor and ask how steeply the walls rise. That curvature — how fast the
    force grows as you push an atom off the bottom — sets how the atoms vibrate, the phonons, and from
    the vibrations follow heat capacity and — for sufficiently anharmonic materials — thermal
    expansion. Squeeze the whole box a little and watch the energy climb: how stiffly it resists gives
    the elastic constants, the material's springiness. These are just the landscape's local shape,
    sampled with cheap evaluations instead of expensive ones.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two ask a little more. A chemical reaction is a trip from one valley to another over the ridge
    between them; the height of the lowest pass through that ridge is the <strong>reaction barrier</strong>,
    which sets how fast the reaction goes. Finding the lowest pass is its own small search, called the
    <strong>nudged elastic band</strong>: lay a chain of intermediate arrangements from one valley to
    the other, pull each arrangement downhill while an artificial spring between neighbors — a bookkeeping
    force, not a real one — keeps the chain from collapsing to one end, and the settled chain traces the
    lowest path over the ridge. Finally, a <strong>free energy</strong> — the quantity that determines
    which phase or arrangement is thermodynamically stable at a given temperature — is not read at one
    point but averaged over a stretch of dynamics at that temperature. All four lean on the same cheap
    evaluation; that is what makes them practical.
  </p>

  <h2><span class="num">§ 4</span>Serving it: the drop-in calculator</h2>

  <p>
    Mature simulation tools already know how to relax a structure, run dynamics, compute phonons — the
    whole catalogue above. What they do not contain is the
    physics. They expect to be handed something that, given the current positions, returns the energy and
    the forces. They call that something a <strong>calculator</strong>, and they ask it the same question
    every step.
  </p>

  <p>
    That slot is exactly the shape of an MLIP. A potential is a function from positions to energy and
    forces; a calculator is an object that returns energy and forces from positions. Wrap the model so it
    answers to the calculator's two questions and it plugs straight into the simulation tool — for
    instance, the widely used Atomic Simulation Environment, or <strong>ASE</strong>. Your relaxation and
    dynamics code never learns which model is behind the slot, so you can swap one potential for another
    without touching the surrounding code.
  </p>

  <div class="cmd">atoms = read("candidate.cif")        # the arrangement
atoms.calc = MyMLIP(checkpoint="...")  # drop the model into the slot

relax(atoms)                          # tool calls the model each step
run_dynamics(atoms, temperature=300)  # so does this — same slot</div>

  <p>
    Installing a potential on a cluster — the right
    Python environment, the matching dependencies, the weights — is fiddly, and doing it once per model
    per machine is the kind of friction that keeps people from trying a second model.
    <strong>Rootstock</strong>, the backend behind these pages, pre-installs many potentials on shared HPC
    clusters and serves each through exactly this drop-in calculator interface. You pick a checkpoint, point
    your simulation at it, and the model runs on the cluster behind the same slot your code already speaks
    to.
  </p>

