  <h2><span class="num">§ 5</span>Where it goes wrong at run time</h2>

  <p>
    The failure that matters here is not the one you would expect. A potential that is a little off on a
    single static structure is rarely the problem. The problem is the trajectory.
  </p>

  <p>
    Run the dynamics loop long enough and the atoms wander. Sooner or later they may reach an arrangement
    unlike anything in the training set — a bond squeezed shorter than any the model was shown, a strange
    transient cluster. There, the model is extrapolating, and Chapter 1's warning comes due: far from its
    training data a potential can be confidently wrong, with no dial that tells you so. A small wrong force
    nudges the atoms somewhere stranger still, which yields a stranger force, and the trajectory can drift
    off course or "blow up" — atoms flying apart, energies running to nonsense — over a long run that looked
    fine for its first million steps. A model can pass every static test and still fail this way, because
    static tests never visit the arrangements a long trajectory eventually finds.
  </p>

  <p>
    Two habits guard against it. Keep the simulation in-distribution — run it on the kinds of systems the
    model was trained for, and be wary when it strays. And where a model offers an <strong>uncertainty
    estimate</strong> — a flag it raises when an arrangement looks unfamiliar — watch that flag and stop, or
    fetch real DFT for the strange region, before the drift compounds.
  </p>

  <p>
    Fast, as long as you stay where the model has been. That caveat kept in view, this is what the
    whole primer was built toward: the energy of a set of atoms — once a slow secret of the electrons —
    is now cheap enough to run forward across millions of atoms and millions of steps that DFT could
    never have afforded. That is what a machine-learned potential is for.
  </p>
</Primer>
